[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426575&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426575&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

What is the "name policy" behind CSNET going to domain names like .CS.NET?
Wasn't the plan to have names like UMASS.EDU registered at NIC which
pointed to some domain server at CSNET which had MF records for the
phonenet site "umass"?

Does this first attempt at using domains for another transport/administration
network means that we will have domain names like:
	network			domain names
	-------			---------------------
	BITNET			BIT.NET
	MAILNET			MAIL.NET or EDUCOM.NET
	UUCP			UCB-UUCP.NET, SEISMO-UUCP.NET, etc.
or is this some transition mechanism to get thru the short term?

One of the driving arguments around CMU for domain names were they
provided a flat name space independent of networks and that each host
would have ONE name. With hosts part of CSNET, MAILNET, UMich net, etc.
and this unwritten new naming policy, the driving flat name space
argument has been undermined.

So what is the deal? Some feedback from the domain gurus would be
nice for a change. 

-Rudy

